Why PiHarness is intentionally small:

The temptation when writing a "pi harness" is to put a lot of
pi-knowledge on the host side — "pi agents need tmux, so we provision
tmux; pi agents use these tools, so we preinstall them." Resisted that.
Everything pi-specific that can live in the guest image SHOULD live in
the guest image, because (a) it ships as a versioned artifact we can
sign/vet later via the hub, (b) it keeps the host side generic so
adding new harnesses doesn't grow the xpressclaw binary, and (c) it
matches how other harness vendors (codex, opencode) will be added —
they can't realistically patch the xpressclaw host.

The pi-specific bits that had to be on the host: workspace mount
(filesystem is a host resource), env seeding for endpoints that ARE
host resources (sidecar, xclaw socket), and image resolution (the
host owns the image cache). That's it.

Why OCI pull stubbed vs. done:

The real OCI pull is non-trivial: parse ghcr.io/foo/bar:tag, fetch
manifest, handle multi-platform manifests, pull blob(s), verify
digest, cache. The oci-client crate does most of it but integrating
adds ~200 lines + a new workspace dep. Pushed to task 4b as its own
unit of work. The stub interface is designed so the real impl drops
in without changing PiHarness or callers — resolve() returns
Result<PathBuf> either way.

Decision tracked in task 4b: OCI artifact (single blob with custom
media type) vs OCI image (multi-layer that needs flattening) vs raw
GH Release asset. Leaning artifact — it's what tools like `oras`
push WASM as, it's what the ecosystem is converging on, and it's a
single HTTP GET after the manifest fetch.

Environment variable naming:

OPENAI_API_BASE is used because it's the de-facto standard any
shell-native agent respects (most libraries read it). When we add a
codex harness or opencode harness they'll pick it up for free. Custom
xpressclaw-specific names would force each harness vendor to add
explicit support; standard names piggyback on existing conventions.
XCLAW_SOCKET is xpressclaw-specific because the xclaw CLI doesn't
exist outside our world.

Placeholder values:

OPENAI_API_BASE=http://127.0.0.1:8935/v1 and XCLAW_SOCKET=/run/xclaw.sock
are both fictional endpoints today. Task 5 makes the socket real;
task 6 makes the LLM endpoint real. Pi harness images can be built
with these values baked in as expectations; when the real
infrastructure lands the values don't change.

Why container_id stays c2w-namespaced when launched via PiHarness:

PiHarness delegates launch() to C2wHarness which formats container_id
as "c2w-{agent_id}". That's semantically correct — the underlying
isolation IS a c2w container; the pi-ness is a configuration choice
layered on top. A user who lists agents and sees "c2w-piggy" is
seeing what the isolation actually is. If we wanted a pi-prefixed ID
we'd have to invent a separate registry. Not worth the bookkeeping.
